node.text:
Rachel had one wish for her 9th birthday: to raise $300 for clean water. After a terrible car accident took her life, people from all over the world donated to help her birthday wish come true. Together, they raised $1,265,823 and changed the lives of 37,770 people in Ethiopia.
 
One year later, Rachel’s mom had the opportunity to visit some of the water projects funded by her birthday campaign. Today, Rachel and the community she inspired have brought clean water to more than 100,000 people.
 
On Monday, we’ll launch a brand new project, inspired by Rachel. Though her life was tragically cut short on this day 10 years ago, Rachel continues to teach us that everyone can make a difference, no matter how young. We will always be grateful for her life and her legacy.

Video: @jamieleighpent
Music: @sleepingatlast

node.text:
When we met Nora in eastern Uganda, she told us that water used to be very limited in her community. It couldn’t be “wasted” on things like hygiene. “We would only use it for cooking,” she said.

This meant that during her period, she never had enough water for herself. She talked about the struggle to cover up the stained clothing she couldn’t wash. She was ashamed to be around people, so she stayed close to home and wouldn’t invite visitors into her house.

In 2019, Nora’s community received a well. Now, she shared, she can shower throughout the day, wash her clothes, and host visitors whenever she wants. As Nora put it, “I am no longer in fear because of my period.”

With access to water, sanitation, and hygiene resources, women like Nora thrive. Learn more and find out how you can help at https://cwtr.org/3uw0MXU (link in bio). #MenstrualHygieneDay

#ThisSeasonWeAreChoosing: Joy

For 10 years, the Slade family has created extravagant holiday card videos featuring everything from underwater renditions of Elvis’s “Blue Christmas” to huge family food fights—all to raise money for clean water.

What began with a campaign that raised $145 in 2011 has grown to over $55,000 and counting. The Slade family’s joyful holiday videos have helped fund clean water for more than 1,300 people in places like Uganda, Cambodia, and Ethiopia!

They shared, “We are so excited that we have had the opportunity to participate in this great cause—helping those in desperate need of clean water. Christmastime is the best time to define what we are all about in the year 2020.”

It’s been an incredible decade with the Slades, and we couldn’t be more grateful for their creativity and generosity over the years. You can see all of the Slade family's videos—including their most recent one!—and support their campaign at http://cwtr.org/2M803vD (link in bio)

Video: @micahslade & @kellyshep13

Greg Klassen (@gregklassenfurniture) is a husband, father, and artist from the Pacific Northwest who generously commits a portion of the proceeds from his water-inspired art to fund water projects.

Greg shared, “I make my River Tables because I love the feeling of nature they evoke, primarily of the life-giving nourishment of water. However, more than nature, I love people. I want to make beautiful art and use it to bring real-life change!”

We are so inspired by you, Greg. Thanks for using your talent to bring clean water to communities in need!

Video: @bigbenbender

You can help support work like this for as little as $5 a month as a member of The Spring. Learn more: charitywater.org/TheSpring

Our local partners are adapting and scaling to protect the most vulnerable from COVID-19. 100% of your donation to our COVID-19 Relief Fund empowers our partners to keep delivering lifesaving water, sanitation, and hygiene resources on the frontlines of the pandemic.
⠀
This #GivingTuesdayNow, we’re coming together as a global community to take action and show our support. Join us: https://cwtr.org/3f69bdZ (link in bio)

node.text:
We’re starting at Lake Victoria, the largest lake in Africa and one of the most common water sources for communities in this area who don’t have access to clean water. You’ll see how our brilliant local partner GOAL is working to make a difference, and you’ll meet a family whose life has never been better.

You can help bring clean and safe water to people in places like Uganda every month by joining The Spring. Learn more at charitywater.org/thespring.

node.text: Kids are doing inspiring, heartwarming, and over-the-top incredible things to raise money for clean water. This year, we created an annual award to celebrate that. Meet 29 certified world-changers at charitywater.org/tinyheroes (link in bio). #charitywaterTinyHeroes

node.text:
“charity: water is so special to me because it opens up the opportunity to better the world to anyone. Even when I was little, it gave me the chance to have a real, positive impact on people's lives across the world. That's pretty cool.” – Bridger

Seven-year-old Bridger gave up his Christmas presents to raise money for clean water in 2010… and then gave up seven more Christmases, raising nearly $54,000 for clean water! Get to know all 29 #charitywaterTinyHeroes at https://cwtr.org/3kVkvim (link in bio).

node.text:
After seeing a video from charity: water, Noa set out to make her own Public Service Announcement for clean water. Thanks in part to Noa’s efforts and the generosity of her friends and family, four communities in Bangladesh now have access to clean and safe water.

“If someone said that kids are too young to make a difference, I would go get my siblings and tell them, ‘Watch this. We’ll prove you wrong.’ Even though we’re small, we can do a lot.” – Noa

We couldn’t agree more: the smallest among us really do have it all figured out. Check out the rest of our #charitywaterTinyHeroes interview with Noa at charitywater.org/stories/tiny-hero-noa!

Photos: @jo__schaus

node.text:
Nathaniel’s fundraising days started with selling popsicles door-to-door. Then came seven (!) birthday campaigns and a bar mitzvah project that included a soccer tournament and a silent auction. All in all, he raised more than $15,000 for clean water.

“On any scale, a kid can make a real difference. A kid can pick up trash on their way to the bus stop or purposefully and consciously be kind to others in their class. You don’t need to be a billionaire or a philanthropist to make a difference.” – Nathaniel

Nathaniel may not be a “tiny” hero anymore (he’s in college… and he’s 6-feet tall), but the impact he has had continues to make a difference. Read the rest of our #charitywaterTinyHeroes interview with Nathaniel at charitywater.org/stories/tiny-hero-nathaniel!

Photos: @jo__schaus

“I liked how I felt involved and that I could actually make a difference. And I liked when people came up to me, smiling at this kid that was actually trying to make a difference. I hope I inspired them to know that everyone can make a difference.” – Maddie

Rain or shine, Maddie stood behind her lemonade stand and raised money for clean water. She even brought in local musicians to keep guests entertained! Meet all 29 legendary #charitywaterTinyHeroes at https://cwtr.org/3kVkvim (link in bio).

Cosette has been selling her stunning art to raise money for people in need of food and clean water since she was three years old. She’s raised over $12,000 for clean water alone! Check out https://cwtr.org/3kVkvim (link in bio) to meet more remarkable #charitywaterTinyHeroes like Cosette.

“Spending the first four years of my life drinking dirty water in Ethiopia, and losing my baby brother because of it, made me want to help make sure no more kids die. Working with charity: water over the past 11 years has helped me feel like I'm helping.” – Tariku

Tariku found a way to transform tragedy into hope, raising more than $40,000 for clean water through nine campaigns. We feel so lucky to work alongside inspiring #charitywaterTinyHeroes like Tariku in our mission to end the water crisis. Learn more at https://cwtr.org/3kVkvim (link in bio).

Rice and beans were on the menu for a full month at Riley’s house in 2009—and the grocery savings went straight to clean water. It’s 12 years later, and while Riley still can’t eat beans, they’re just as committed to changing the world for the better.

“I’m living in D.C. and interning on Capitol Hill. That’s where this has led me to. And I think that’s probably true for every child when you support their passion to change the world. It’s going to evolve into even more meaningful things as they get older.” – Riley

You can read the rest of our #charitywaterTinyHeroes interview with Riley at charitywater.org/stories/tiny-hero-riley. You can also donate to Riley's new campaign to help even more people get clean water! Go, go now! charitywater.org/riley-goodfellow/not-so-little-tiny-hero

Photos: @jo__schaus

In 2014, siblings Aviva and Sage decided to go trick-or-treating as the “Knights of the mycharity: water Table.” Instead of a pumpkin full of candy, they came home with over $100 for clean water!

We are so inspired by all of the creative ways kids have raised money for clean water. Check out https://cwtr.org/3kVkvim (link in bio) for more #charitywaterTinyHeroes stories like this one!

In 2008, @charitywater founder and CEO @scottharrison bet that he could raise 10x as much money as 7-year-old Max, who had given up his birthday to raise money for clean water. Scott promised to give a public concession speech if Max won… and he did, raising $21,000!

“My pitch was essentially, ‘This isn’t fair.’ Here I am, a 7-year-old child, and there are seven-year-old children in a different country dying because they do not have access to a basic human right. It felt like, ‘I have clean water. They should have clean water, too.’” – Max

Max is in college now, and he’s still determined to change the world. Check out charitywater.org/stories/tiny-hero-max-s for more with our #charitywaterTinyHeroes interview with Max!
